			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Domain-Specific Metamodelling Languages for Software Language Engineering</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/SteffenZschaler.html">Steffen Zschaler</a>, <a href="../profile/DimitriosSKolovos.html">Dimitrios S. Kolovos</a>, <a href="../profile/NikolaosDrivalos.html">Nikolaos Drivalos</a>, <a href="../profile/RichardFPaige.html">Richard F. Paige</a>, <a href="../profile/AwaisRashid.html">Awais Rashid</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_23">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_23</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It proposes/analyses metamodelling languages tailored to defining and engineering other languages.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> Such metamodelling languages are typically realized as workbench capabilities and supporting tools.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The goal is to better engineer domain-specific languages via dedicated metamodelling support.
</li></ul></li></ul>
